zlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Evan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh (southern): from the personal name <i>Evan</i>, itself from <i>Ieuan</i>, a Welsh derivative of Latin <i>Johannes</i> (English <i>John</i>). See   Evans  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bevan","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Iefan</i> ‘son of Evan’, with fused patronymic marker <i>(a)p</i>. Compare   Evan   and   Evans  ."]},{"name":"Heaven","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Evan  .","English: variant of   Haven  .","Irish (Tipperary): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEimhín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eimhín</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>éimh</i> ‘swift’, ‘prompt, ready’."]},{"name":"Haven","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) harbor’, from Middle English <i>haven</i> (Old English <i>hæfen</i> ‘haven’).","Welsh (Monmouthshire): variant of   Evan  .","Dutch: variant of   Haveman  , or possibly a topographic name from <i>haven</i> ‘port, harbour’. See also   De Haven  ."]},{"name":"Evans","meanings":["Welsh: derivative of   Evan  , from <i>Efan</i>, <i>Ifan</i>, medieval forms of <i>Ieuan</i> (from Latin <i>Johannes</i>, the source of English <i>John</i>), dating from <i>c.</i> 1500, with the post-medieval patronymic suffix <i>-s</i>. Welsh <i>Sion</i> was a separate borrowing of English <i>John</i>, and <i>Evan</i> (<i>Ieuan</i>) and <i>Sion</i> developed as independent names."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"\"Gethyn\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from a lenited adjectival form of the byname <i>Cethin</i> ‘dusky, swarthy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gethen","meanings":["Traditional: from a lenited adjectival form of the byname <i>Cethin</i> ‘dusky, swarthy’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"William \"Gethyn\" Ap Evan was born about 1420, in Baglan, Glamorgan, Wales as the son of Evan Robert. He had at least 5 sons with Miss ap Einon."},"et":{"abt 1420–":"umbes 1420–Surnud","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1417–Female":"1417–Surnud","1424–Female":"1424–Surnud","1444–Male":"1444–Surnud","1445–Male":"1445–Surnud","1446–Male":"1446–Surnud","1448–Male":"1448–Surnud","1450–Male":"1450–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1450":"1450","abt 1450":"umbes 1450","abt 1420":"umbes 1420","abt 1444":"umbes 1444","1448":"1448","abt 1445":"umbes 1445","abt 1446":"umbes 1446","1446":"1446","1424":"1424","1445":"1445","abt 1448":"umbes 1448","1444":"1444","1420":"1420","1417":"1417","of Baglan, Glmrgn, Wls":"Baglan, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt 1420–":"noin 1420–Kuol